# MANDATORY: Always Record Stats

When running `vfs` commands in this project, **never** pass `--no-record` unless explicitly testing or benchmarking in a throwaway context.

Every invocation should log to `~/.vfs/history.jsonl` so the owner can visualize performance trends (tokens saved, reduction %, files scanned, duration) over time.

## Rules

1. **Do NOT add `--no-record`** to `vfs` commands. Recording is on by default — just leave it.
2. **Use `--stats`** when demonstrating vfs output or verifying a new parser, so the user can see the token efficiency numbers inline.
3. After significant changes (new parser, refactor), run `vfs stats` to show cumulative lifetime stats.

## Data location

- History file: `~/.vfs/history.jsonl` (append-only JSONL)
- Each entry records: timestamp, project path, filter, files scanned/matched, raw vs vfs bytes/lines, tokens saved, reduction %, duration
- View summary: `vfs stats`
- Reset if needed: `vfs stats --reset`
